{It is widely known that White's main setup against the Bogoljubov Defence is
based on g2-g3 and Bg2. While aesthetically this looks pleasing for White, we
should also understand why this system is more effective than the more
"neutral" one, based on e2-e4 and Be2/d3. Abstractly, even before starting to
examine concrete positions, I would like to point out that g2-g3 reduces
Black's influence on the dark squares by controlling f4 and h4. The following
game illustrates Black's possibilities when White lacks this influence.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2 d6 7. e4 e5 8. d5 {
In the schemes with g2-g3, where the e-pawn is on its initial squares, when
Black attacks the centre, he needs to waste time to induce d4-d5 (...Nc6,
d4-d5 ... Nb8) . But due to his hurried occupation of the centre, White does
not have any favourable ways of maintaining it.} (8. Be2 exd4 {[%csl Re4]
leaves the e4-pawn hanging.}) (8. Bd3 Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Nxf3 exd4 11. Nxd4 O-O
12. Kf1 Nc6 $17 {offers Black excellent play on the dark squares.}) 8... a5 9.
b3 O-O 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O {The first thing we notice is that without g2-g3,
Black has the "King's Indian" plan based on ...Nh5.} Nc5 $1 (11... Nh5 $2 {
is premature due to} 12. Nxe5 {, winning a pawn.}) 12. Qc2 Nh5 $1 {But now it
is a good moment for this manoeuvre.} 13. Ne1 ({The point is that after} 13.
Nxe5 $2 Nf4 $19 {[%csl Re2,Re5] White's pieces are hanging.}) ({The regrouping
chosen by White is unfortunate, but Black has the initiative anyway. For
instance} 13. g3 f5 $132) ({or} 13. Rfe1 Nf4 14. Bf1 f5 15. g3 fxe4 16. Nxe4
Nh3+) 13... Nf4 14. Bf3 f5 15. Rc1 fxe4 {Oll decides to treat the position as
if it was a King's Indian with the dark-squared bishops already exchanged.} ({
But with his g-pawn on its initial square, Black could use the sixth rank for
the rook's insertion into the attack:} 15... Qh4 $1 16. b4 axb4 17. axb4 Rf6 $1
18. g3 (18. bxc5 $6 {loses even more quickly to} Rh6 19. h3 Nxh3+ $1 {mating!})
18... Qh3 19. Bg2 Nxg2 20. Nxg2 Rh6 21. Nf3 fxe4 $19) 16. Nxe4 Bf5 {Since
Black does not have a "bad" bishop, this structure favours him compared to the
King's Indian. And the knight's activity on f4 also counts, of course.} 17. b4
axb4 18. axb4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Bxe4 20. Qxe4 Qg5 21. Kh1 Ra2 22. Rc2 Ra1 $17 {
With complete black domination.} 0-1

