{As mentioned above, after g2-g3 Black usually has to invest two tempi into
inducing d4-d5. This results in some advance in development for White, due to
which a plan based on ...f7-f5 is not very probable in the near future. On the
contrary, it is White who can play f2-f4, as the g3-pawn sustains this action
and his bishop does not obstruct the e-file. But the good news is that with
the dark-squared bishops off the board, Black can simply maintain the kingside
tension and look for counterplay on the opposite wing.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Nc3 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 8. Rc1 d6 9. Bg2 O-O 10.
d5 Nxc3 11. Rxc3 Nb8 12. O-O e5 {Instead of the usual plan based on c4-c5,
White now chooses to start attacking on the kingside.} 13. Nd2 Nd7 14. e4 a5
15. f4 {All this looks very logical. White is a few tempi ahead in development,
and his rook's activity along the third rank looks impressive. But it is
precisely in such situations when we can understand Black's deep philosophy in
this system. His almost perfect stability on the dark squares and complete
lack of weaknesses offer him clearer prospects to improve his position than
White could dream of.} Nc5 {A calm move, continuing development.} ({By the way,
there does not seem to be anything wrong with} 15... exf4 16. gxf4 f5 {when
White's centre would lose its flexibility. More about ...exf4 in later
examples.}) 16. f5 ({With his e4-pawn attacked, White does not have a quick
way of increasing the pressure on e5. And after} 16. fxe5 Qxe5 {there is no
obvious way to eliminate the blockade on e5. This makes the last move logical,
as it offers White a slow but consistent kingside attack. If we consider only
the right half of the board, we could think of a reversed King's Indian, but
if we switch to the other half, we notice that White also has the advanced
King's Indian centre! And yet, the paradox continues. Although all those
elements seem to be to his disadvantage, Black has just enough counterplay.
One important detail is that after the exchange of two minor pieces, his
relative lack of space does not hamper his coordination.}) 16... f6 17. h4 ({
Since Black's counterplay will start with ...b7-b5, it makes sense to check
what would happen after} 17. a4 Bd7 18. b3 {The queenside position looks bad
for White as Black has a perfect blockade. But if White manages to keep it
closed, he will have chances to make progress with his attack.} c6 19. g4 (19.
h4 {leaves the pawn on f5 vulnerable after} cxd5 20. exd5 {Otherwise Black
breaks with ...b7-b5.} g6 $1 21. g4 gxf5 22. gxf5 Kh8 {and suddenly it will be
Black who is attacking along the g-file.}) ({Since in the mainline the rook
will be exposed on c3,} 19. Re3 {deserves mentioning, even though it wastes a
tempo.} Be8 $1 {Black, too, takes a piece out of the enemy pawns' range.} 20.
g4 b5 $1 {Black's attack is by no means slower than White's.}) 19... b5 (19...
Be8 20. Qe2 b5 $11 {is also possible and if} 21. dxc6 $2 bxa4 $17) 20. dxc6 b4
21. Rg3 Bxc6 {White has managed to keep the queenside closed, but things look
even worse than before for him, as ...Bxa4 is a serious potential threat.} 22.
h4 Kf7 $1 23. g5 Ke8 {Black's king moves into safety, and after the inevitable
opening of the kingside he has chances to reach a promising endgame.}) 17...
Bd7 18. g4 b5 $1 {A typical Bogoindian counterattack, which is usually not
available in the King's Indian. In the absence of the dark-squared bishops,
the knight on c5 maintains its stability after the opening of the c-file.} 19.
b3 {White tries to keep the wing blocked to have free hands for his attack.
But the last move offers Black a new target.} ({It may have been better to
allow the opening of the queenside with, say,} 19. Rg3 bxc4 20. Nxc4 Rfb8 21.
Rf2 Rb4 22. Qc1 Bb5 23. Rc2 a4 {Black is very active, but White has chances to
keep his position together.}) 19... b4 $1 {Blocking the queenside is justified
by the possibility of opening the a-file. Otherwise, it is just a perfect
blockade on the dark squares.} 20. Rh3 {Preparing an unsound pawn sacrifice.} (
20. Rg3 {makes more sense, but Black's initiative develops faster after} a4 21.
g5 axb3 22. axb3 Ra2 $15 {followed by ...Rfa8.}) 20... a4 21. g5 $2 fxg5 22.
Qg4 gxh4 23. Rxh4 axb3 24. axb3 Ra2 25. Nf3 Qf6 26. Qh3 Nd3 27. Qg4 ({Sadly,} 
27. Rxh7 $2 {runs into} Rxg2+ $1 $19) 27... Nf4 28. Rf2 Rxf2 29. Kxf2 Ra8 $19 {
, and White resigned after 39 completely unnecessary further moves.} 0-1

