{[#] I have mentioned above that Black can meet f2-f4 with ...exf4, aiming for
kingside counterplay. Here is a typical example in an almost identical
position:} 1. f4 exf4 $5 {If Black allows f4-f5, White is slightly better.} (
1... Nc5 {would transpose to the previous game.}) 2. gxf4 f5 {We are getting
used to the small paradoxes already. Despite White's superior development,
Black does not fear opening the centre. Since e4-e5 is not possible, the
f4-pawn will soon turn into a weakness.} 3. Qc1 $6 {A slightly mysterious
regrouping. As we will see, White intends to use his queen for the attack from
afar.} ({Black does not have problems after the more natural} 3. Rg3 {either:}
Nc5 4. Re1 fxe4 5. Nxe4 Nxe4 6. Bxe4 Qf6 7. Qh5 Bf5 8. Bxf5 Qxf5 9. Qxf5 Rxf5
10. Re7 {1/2-1/2 Rashkovsky,N (2530) -Gipslis,A (2465) Moscow 1992}) 3... fxe4
4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Re3 Bxe4 6. Bxe4 Qf6 $15 {Abstractly, White played quite
logically, and all his pieces will participate in the kingside attack soon.
But the dominant knight on c5 and White's weaknesses in the centre will have
more impact.} 7. Qb1 g6 8. Rg3 Kh8 9. Kh1 Rae8 10. Rh3 Kg7 11. Rg1 (11. f5 {
only increases Black's control over the dark squares after} g5) 11... Nc5 12.
Bc2 Rg8 $6 {An over-cautious move, anticipating White's threats.} ({Everything
was ready for the counterattack:} 12... Re2 $1 13. Rhg3 ({Or if} 13. f5 g5 14.
Rxg5+ Qxg5 15. Rg3 Qxg3 16. hxg3 Rfe8 {with a decisive attack due to the
queen's passivity.}) 13... Qh4 14. h3 (14. R1g2 {reduces White's attacking
potential and is most simply met with} Rxg2 15. Kxg2 Rf6 {threatening ... Qxf4.
And if} 16. f5 Qxc4 17. fxg6 Qxd5+ 18. Kg1 h5 $19 {with an extra pawn and a
dominating position.}) 14... Rf6 15. Bxg6 {This was probably what Anand feared,
but it does not offer White real attacking chances.}) 13. b3 Re2 $17 14. a3 $6
{With so many mutual kingside ideas available, this plan is not to the point.}
(14. Rhg3 {would have still maintained approximate equality:} Qh4 15. R1g2 Rxg2
16. Kxg2 Qf6 17. f5 g5 18. Qe1 $11 {Avoiding problems along the e-file. Black
is very stable and has little to complain about, but making progress is not
simple.}) 14... Rf2 $6 {In this phase, both players seem to neglect the
importance of the open e-file.} ({Even with delay, the reserve rook should
have been thrown into the fight:} 14... Rge8 $1 15. Rhg3 Qh4 16. h3 R8e3 $1 17.
Qb2+ Kf7 $19) 15. b4 $6 {Consistent but bad.} (15. f5 $1 g5 16. Re1 {(The
e-file again!)} g4 $5 17. Re7+ $5 {The only way to avoid being squeezed.} Qxe7
18. Rxh7+ Kxh7 19. f6+ Qe4+ $1 {Black should not allow fxe7, of course.} 20.
Bxe4+ Kh6 $13 {with complicated play and mutual chances.}) 15... axb4 16. axb4
Nd7 17. Bf5 Nf8 18. Qe4 Kh8 {White's "attacking fury" has only helped Black to
regroup and consolidate his kingside. The pawn on f4 is doomed and so is
White's game.} 19. Bc8 Rxf4 20. Qe2 b6 $19 21. Re3 Rf2 22. Qg4 g5 23. Re8 Ng6
24. Rxg8+ Kxg8 25. Be6+ Kg7 26. c5 Qe5 0-1

