{Continuing the discussion about Black's kingside resources, we will mention
an idea available (but most of the times questionable) in the King's Indian:
The expansion with ...g7-g5. With the dark-squared bishop on the board, this
would be strategically risky, but in the Bogoindian the dangers (if any) can
only be tactical.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Nc3
d6 7. Bg2 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Ne4 9. Rc1 Nxc3 10. Rxc3 e5 11. d5 Nb8 12. e4 O-O 13.
Nh4 a5 14. O-O Na6 15. Qe1 {We can notice that Piket tried to prepare his
kingside attack more thoroughly than in the previous game. But Anand
immediately put an end to his dreams.} g5 $5 {Typically for this system, Black
can place as many pawns as he likes on the dark squares, without fearing the
weaknesses created on the light squares.} ({He can also adopt the usual plan:} 
15... Nc5 16. f4 exf4 17. gxf4 Rb8 18. Rg3 b5 19. cxb5 Rxb5 20. b3 Rb4 21. Qa1
f5 $132 {with active counterplay.}) 16. Nf5 $6 {As tempting the invasion of
the "weak" square may be, the position following the exchange on f5 will turn
completely static, offering Black the more pleasant side of a possibly still
equal fight.} (16. Nf3 {was more principled.} Nc5 17. Nd2 f5 18. f4 {White
tries to make use of his better development by opening the centre. Otherwise
Black will take over the initiative.} exf4 19. gxf4 fxe4 {An interesting way
of maintaining the central stability.} 20. Rg3 (20. fxg5 Bf5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal
Gc5d3] consolidates the central pawn, ensuring a later ...Nd3.}) 20... g4 $1
$11 {with chances for both sides.}) 16... Bxf5 17. exf5 Nc5 18. Be4 {Piket
decides to set up a blockade on the light squares. But there is a significant
difference between the blocking pieces. While the knight cannot be attacked,
the bishop will be permanently under the knight's pressure. This will
determine the character of the game as one-sided.} (18. f4 {offers better
chances for a double-edged game.} gxf4 19. gxf4 ({If} 19. Rxf4 Qg5 20. Rh4 Nd7
$5 {[%cal Gc5d7,Gd7f6] Transferring the knight to the even better blocking
square f6.} 21. b3 Nf6 22. a3 h5 {[%cal Gg8g7,Gb7b5] Black has a harmonious
kingside position and after ...Kg7 he can also consider opening the queenside
with ...b7-b5.}) 19... e4 $5 (19... f6 {is also good, as} 20. fxe5 dxe5 {
does not shake his stability.}) 20. Rg3+ Kh8 21. Qc3+ {Otherwise ...Qf6.} f6
22. b3 {White has to fight against Black's knight.} Qd7 23. a3 Rae8 24. b4 axb4
25. axb4 Nd3 $11) 18... Qf6 19. f3 Rfe8 20. Qe3 Kg7 21. Kg2 h5 {Black starts
to display territorial ambitions.} 22. Rh1 Rg8 $1 {This is by far better than
the similar rook move in the previous game. Black prepares not only ...g5-g4
but also the king's evacuation to e7.} 23. h3 $6 {Up to this point Black's
position was just more pleasant to play, but the last move finally dooms White
to a strategically bad position.} ({He should have stuck to the usual plan
starting with} 23. b3 g4 24. h3 gxf3+ 25. Qxf3 Kf8 $1 {[%cal Gf8e7]} 26. Re3
Rg5 27. Rf1 Ke7 28. Bc2 Rag8 29. Qe2 Kd8 {True, Black's play is easier, but
White maintains some chances, too.} 30. a3 e4 (30... a4 {forces the exchange
of the minor pieces, with approximate equality:} 31. b4 Nb3 32. Bxb3 axb3 33.
Rxb3 Rxf5 $11) 31. b4 axb4 32. axb4 Nd7 33. Bxe4 Qd4 34. Ra3 Nb6 {Black's
activity offers him excellent compensation for the pawn, but the position
remains unclear.}) 23... h4 24. g4 Rgb8 {With the kingside blocked, Black
switches to the other wing.} 25. Rhc1 ({White should have fought against ...
b7-b5 with} 25. Bd3 $5 {Exchanging the bishop is out of the question, but
White might have feared that a well-timed ...e5-e4 would put him in danger.})
25... b5 26. cxb5 Rxb5 27. R1c2 Rab8 28. Qd2 Qd8 29. b3 Qe7 {At this stage,
Anand was mainly worried about an exchange sacrifice on c5, causing him to
play a series of over-cautious moves and losing coordination. In principle,
this is White's only constructive plan, should Black allow it, but concretely
it does not work.} ({Black should have continued his main plan without being
afraid of ghosts:} 29... Rb4 $1 30. Rc4 ({Anand gives} 30. Rxc5 dxc5 31. Rxc5 {
, but after} a4 $19 {Black's initiative develops more quickly, as the white
king is exposed.}) 30... R8b6 31. Kf1 f6 32. Kg2 Qb8 $17 {followed by ...
a5-a4 soon.}) 30. Rc4 R8b6 31. Kf1 Qd8 32. Ke2 Kf6 {Black frees his queen from
the task of defending g5 without weakening the seventh rank. While the move is
correct, the king's position on f6 will later offer White an unexpected chance.
} (32... f6 {was simpler, as it is highly unlikely that White will ever take
on c7 with check.}) 33. Qc1 {I assume that at this height Piket had already
designed his tactical idea, but it took him some time to find the best
positioning.} Qb8 34. Qe3 Ra6 $2 ({Now was the last chance for Black to break
on the queenside:} 34... a4 $1 35. bxa4 Ra5 36. Qa3 Rb1 37. Qc3 Qb6 {Suddenly
the queen's intrusion to g1 is a big threat.} 38. Rc1 Rxc1 39. Qxc1 Qa6 $19 {
and White cannot prevent the intrusion anymore.}) 35. Bd3 $1 {This works only
when the bishop is defended by the queen, as otherwise the pawn on d5 would be
lost after the exchange. And the queen needs to have direct access to the
g-file, making e3 the best square for it.} Ra7 $2 {Completely losing the feel
for danger.} (35... Nxd3 36. Qxd3 Ra7 $11 {would have maintained equality.})
36. f4 $3 {A fantastic pawn break which should have won the game. With his
pieces massed on the queenside, Black cannot defend the kingside dark squares
anymore.} ({Anand's previous manoeuvring is even more difficult to understand
if we mention that the idea he had feared, namely} 36. Rxc5 Rxc5 37. Rxc5 dxc5
38. Qxc5 {offers White enough compensation for the exchange, for instance} Qb6
39. Qf8 $1 {and Black has to find the only adequate defence against the
threats Qd8+ and Qh6:} e4 $1 {clearing the e5-square for the king.} 40. Qh8+
Ke7 41. Qe5+ Kd7 42. fxe4 a4 $11 {and the game is likely to end in a draw by
perpetual.}) 36... gxf4 ({Or if} 36... exf4 37. Qd4+ Ke7 38. Rxc5 Rxc5 39. f6+
Kd8 40. Rxc5 dxc5 41. Qxc5 $18) 37. g5+ $1 Kg7 (37... Kxg5 38. Rxf4 exf4 39.
Qe7+ Kh6 40. Qxh4+ Kg7 41. f6+ {mates soon.}) 38. f6+ Kg8 39. Rxc5 $2 {
Probably a time-trouble mistake.} (39. Qg1 $1 {would have left Black helpless
against g5-g6, for instance} Nxd3 40. g6 $18) 39... fxe3 40. Rxb5 {White did
not have any compensation for the queen and lost soon.} Qe8 41. Rc6 e4 42. Bc2
Ra8 43. Rb7 Qe5 44. Rbxc7 Qf4 {This game is instructive as it illustrates not
only Black's possible plans but also White's anti-blockading ideas.  0-1 (44)
Piket,J (2570)-Anand,V (2725) Wijk aan Zee 1996} 0-1

[Event "Jacobs,B - Ivkov,B Manchester"]
