{We will now switch our attention to the other wing. The traditional King's
Indian plan is c4-c5, which sometimes requires a preparatory b2-b4. Once again,
we will find out that the absence of the dark-squared bishops offers Black
additional defensive and even counter-attacking ideas.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 e6 3.
c4 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 {In our repertoire we avoid taking on
d2 so quickly, as this allows White the knight's undisturbed development to c3.
But structurally, the system played in this game is very similar to our
mainlines.} d6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Bg2 e5 9. O-O Re8 {In view of the threat ...
e5-e4-e3, White has to advance his e-pawn.} 10. e4 Bg4 {The d4-square faces
the danger of an invasion after ... Nc6, so White has to settle for the
blocked centre.} 11. d5 Bxf3 {In some of the previous games, the bishop has
played an important role, but in principle, exchanging it for a knight
increases Black's control over the dark squares.} (11... a5 12. Ne1 {followed
by Nd3, the bishop would be out of play.}) 12. Bxf3 a5 13. a3 $6 {White
follows the usual King's Indian patterns. But in fact, the last move is an
inaccuracy already, as it prematurely weakens the b3-square in a moment when
White is not ready for the queenside attack.} Na6 14. Rab1 ({If} 14. Na4 {
the best way to defend a5 is} Nc5 (14... b6 15. b4 {offers White normal
queenside play, as ... c7-c6 is not available anymore.}) 15. Nxc5 dxc5 {
and it is hard to believe that White can shatter Black's stability in any way.}
) 14... c6 $1 {Still waiting for White to commit himself completely.} ({
Blocking the queenside with} 14... c5 $6 {is not a good idea as White gets
absolute control on the light squares while Black does not have any
counterplay.} 15. Bd1 g6 16. Ba4 {taking measures against ...Nd7 as an answer
to f2-f4.} Red8 17. Rbe1 {followed by f2-f4, with consistent pressure.}) 15. b4
$6 {Allowing Black to solve all his problems.} ({White could have played
something neutral such as} 15. Rfc1 {but it would not have been clear how to
develop the initiative afterwards anyway.}) 15... axb4 16. axb4 c5 $1 {This is
a typical Bogo Indian resource. In the King's Indian, with the dark-squared
bishops on the board, White could fight against the blockade on c5 or simply
attack the knight on b4. Black's g7-bishop would have remained a mere
spectator.} 17. b5 (17. bxc5 Nxc5 {or}) (17. Na2 cxb4 18. Nxb4 Nc5 {leave
Black with a pleasant blockade.}) 17... Nb4 {Black has achieved comfortable
equality.} 18. Ra1 Nd7 19. Be2 Nb6 {The other knight has also reached an
excellent square. The plan in the next phase is to fight for the a-file, but
due to White's huge space advantage and the blocked centre and queenside, it
is hard to believe that Black will get realistic winning chances.} 20. h4 Reb8
21. Kg2 Qd8 22. h5 $6 {A significant strategic mistake, conceding control over
the square g5. Any neutral move would have maintained equality.} h6 {Planning .
..Qg5.} 23. f4 Qf6 {It appears that White cannot maintain control and has to
place just another pawn on a light square.} 24. f5 Qg5 25. Qb2 $2 {After this
concession, allowing the enemy queen's intrusion to e3, it is hard to believe
that White can save the game.} ({True, the endgame arising after} 25. Qxg5 hxg5
{looks worrying for White. The immediate threat is ...Nc2, getting control
over the a-file and transferring the knight to d4. But White can save the game
due to Black's complete lack of pawn breaks.} 26. Rfc1 Rxa1 27. Rxa1 Nc2 28.
Ra2 Nd4 29. Kf2 $1 (29. Bd3 {saves the pawn on c4 but allows} g4 $1 {when
Black has a clear plan to make progress:} 30. Kf2 Nd7 31. Ra1 Nf6 32. Rh1 Ra8
$19) 29... Nxe2 30. Kxe2 Nxc4 31. Nd1 f6 32. Kd3 Nb6 33. Ne3 Kf7 34. g4 Ke7 (
34... Ra8 $4 {even loses:} 35. Rxa8 Nxa8 36. Nc4 Ke7 37. b6 {[%csl Ya8,Gb6,Rb7]
[%cal Gd3c3,Gc3b3,Gb3a4,Ga4b5,Ye7d7,Yd7e7,Rc4a5] followed by the king's
transfer to b5 at a moment when Black must play ...Ke7, followed by Na5.}) 35.
Nc4 Nxc4 36. Kxc4 Kd7 37. b6 $11 {with an obvious draw.}) 25... Rxa1 26. Rxa1
Qe3 {The threat ...Nd3 is very hard to meet.} 27. f6 $5 (27. Rd1 Ra8 28. Qc1
Qxc1 29. Rxc1 Ra3 {dooms White to perpetual passivity. Black can transfer his
king to e7 to secure the pawn on d6 against a later b5-b6 and Nb5, and then
the knight to f6, followed by ... Na2.}) 27... Nd3 28. Qb1 (28. Bxd3 Qxd3 {
followed by ...Nxc4 offers Black a decisive attack.}) 28... Nf4+ 29. gxf4 Qxc3
30. Qe1 Qxe1 31. Rxe1 Nd7 {The knight arrives just in time to stabilize the
centre.} 32. fxg7 exf4 33. Kf3 Ra8 34. Rg1 Ra2 35. Bf1 Ra1 36. Kf2 (36. Kxf4
Ne5 {followed by ...Nxc4.}) 36... Ne5 37. b6 Ra2+ 38. Be2 f3 {As inspiring
this game might have been in its final phase, the analysis reveals the fact
that Black's queenside plan is enough to equalize without problems, but not
more.} 0-1

[Event "Kuzmin,A - Hernandez,O, Andorra"]
[Site "?"]
