{[%evp 0,4,18,18,25,20,7] [#] The next game features a more consistent white
plan after the opening from the previous example, even though it is hard to
evaluate how dangerous it is if Black plays correctly.} 1. b3 {For the time
being, White consolidates his queenside in order to be able to manoeuvre at
his leisure.} Na6 2. Bg2 Nc5 {It is hard to refrain from such a move, but
Black can also play} (2... c6 {at once, to keep the possibility of switching
to the plan from the previous game if given the chance.}) 3. Rab1 {Just giving
a hint that at some point he might play a2-a3.} c6 4. Qe2 Qc7 5. Rfd1 h6 ({
A more logical kingside regrouping is} 5... g6 6. Qe3 Kg7 {followed by ...
h7-h5, restricting the white bishop.}) 6. Bh3 {White does not have a clear
plan yet, but the bishop's pressure is slightly unpleasant.} cxd5 $2 {This is
precisely what Black should not do when he cannot control the c-file nor
advance his b-pawn.} ({Hernandez wanted to prepare ...Qb6, as if} 6... Qb6 $6
7. dxc6 $1 {forces} Qxc6 8. f3 $16 {White has achieved a favourable version of
a structure examined later. His knight prevents ...b7-b5 and the bishop makes
sure there will be no knight transfer to d4.}) ({But} 6... Red8 {defending d6,
was better. For instance:} 7. Qe3 Qb6 8. a3 ({White has to be careful, too.
Insisting on the pressure along the d-file leaves the queenside vulnerable:} 8.
Rd2 Qb4 9. f3 h5 10. Rbd1 $6 a4 $15) 8... Qc7 9. b4 ({Having said "A"...} 9.
Rdc1 {can be answered with} a4 10. b4 Nb3 {[%cal Gb3d4] followed by ...Nd4.})
9... axb4 10. axb4 Na4 $11 {After the knight exchange, Black will not have any
problems, while if} 11. Ne2 $6 c5 $1 12. b5 Nb6 $15 {the hanging pawns on e4
and c4 cause Black problems fighting for the a-file.}) 7. cxd5 Qb6 $6 {Going
all the way towards the disaster.} ({Neutral moves such as} 7... h5 $14 {
would have kept Black in the game.}) 8. Na4 $1 Nxa4 9. bxa4 Qa7 10. Rdc1 {
After the opening of the b- and c-files Black's queenside is in danger. And
his knight is almost completely dominated by the bishop.} Re7 11. Rc4 g6 12.
Qb2 Ne8 13. Qb6 Qxb6 14. Rxb6 Kf8 15. f3 {A useful move, not only
consolidating the pawn on e4 but also clearing the path for the king's
centralisation. Such moves can be very unpleasant when the opponent is almost
paralysed, frequently inducing mistakes.} Rd8 $6 {In fact it is hard to
criticise this move, which just loses the pawn on b7 earlier than it should be.
} ({If Black sticks to a passive plan with, say} 15... h5 {White's winning
plan is as follows:} 16. Rc1 (16. Bc8 {is premature due to} Nc7 $1 17. Bxb7 Rb8
{[%csl Rb7][%cal Gc7d5] and White cannot double rooks on the b-file to prevent
...Nxd5.}) 16... Kg7 17. Bc8 Rb8 (17... Nc7 {leaves White in control after} 18.
Bxb7 Rb8 19. Rcb1) 18. Kf2 Nc7 19. Bh3 Ne8 20. Ke3 Kf8 21. Kd3 Kg7 {Now that
his king controls several important squares along the c-file, White can
finally go for the b7-pawn:} 22. Rc8 Rxc8 23. Bxc8 Rc7 24. Bxb7 Rc1 25. Bc6 Nf6
26. Bb5 {with every chance to win.}) 16. Bc8 Rc7 17. Rxc7 Nxc7 18. Bxb7 Rb8 19.
Rb3 {For the time being, White's extra pawn is not that relevant, but his
domination is crushing. And in the long run, the pawn on a5 will be weak.} Ke7
20. Kf2 Kd8 21. Ke3 f5 ({This offers White new targets on the kingside. But if
} 21... Ke7 {White wins by approaching with the king:} 22. Kd3 Kd8 23. Kc4 Ke7
24. Bc6 Rxb3 25. axb3 $18) 22. exf5 ({There wasn't anything wrong with} 22. Kd3
{either.}) 22... gxf5 23. g4 f4+ 24. Ke4 Ke7 25. h4 Ne8 26. Bc6 Rxb3 27. axb3
Nc7 28. Kf5 Kf7 29. Bb5 1-0

