{As mentioned before, Black's light-squared bishop can be an important
attacking piece. Here is an example of how dangerous it can become if White
carries out his queenside attack too much in King's Indian style.} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 Nc6 3. Nf3 e6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Qe7 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 O-O 8. O-O d6 9.
e4 e5 10. d5 Nb8 11. Ne1 a5 12. Nd3 Na6 13. a3 {White has a harmonious setup
and will be able to start a pawn attack on either wing.} Bd7 ({Our repertoire
line goes} 13... Bg4 14. f3 Bd7 {The weakness of the g1-a7 diagonal and the
passive g2-bishop offer Black certain tactical possibilities if the centre
opens.}) 14. b4 c6 15. Qb3 $6 ({With the pawn on f2, White could play} 15. dxc6
bxc6 16. Nb3 axb4 17. axb4 $14 {, when} d5 {looks less playable than with the
pawn on f3.}) 15... cxd5 $1 16. cxd5 axb4 $1 17. axb4 Nc7 {Suddenly there is
not much left of White's attack. On the contrary, Black can use the b5-square
for both his queenside minor pieces, and it is White who needs to think about
equality already.} 18. Rfc1 Nb5 19. Qb2 h5 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. Ra1 Rb8 22. Ra5 $2
{Since White is not able to attack the knight in the near future, this move
just misplaces the rook, offering Black a few tempi to develop his initiative.
Besides, the knight was heading for d4 anyway, clearing the path for the
bishop.} (22. h4 Ng4 {causes some kingside discomfort.}) ({White should have
taken measures against ...Nd4 with} 22. Ne1 {for instance} Rc8 (22... Nd4 23.
Nd3 $11) 23. Rc1 $11 {and it is hard to believe that Black can get more than
just a pleasant position.}) 22... Rc8 23. Bf1 {White anticipates the danger of
...Nd4 followed by ...Bb5 but weakens his king's defence. Even though Black's
bishop remained immobile until the end of the game, we can notice that the
threat ...Bb5 was not weaker than the execution. And in some lines below, the
bishop will play an important part.} ({Other moves are hardly better:} 23. Ne1
{runs into:} Nc3 24. Ra3 Ne2+ 25. Kh1 Ng4 $19 {with the brutal threat of mate
in one.}) ({Or if} 23. Ra1 Nd4 {the fork on e2 prevents} 24. Rc1 {[%csl Rc1,
Rg1][%cal Gd4e2]}) 23... Nd4 24. Ne1 Qd8 $5 {The idea of transferring the
queen to b6 is more typical for positions with the pawn on f3. But here it
will work, too.} ({The immediate} 24... h4 $17 {was strong, too.}) 25. Kg2 h4
26. Bd3 h3+ ({Another promising attacking plan was} 26... Nh5 27. Ndf3 Nxf3 28.
Nxf3 Qf6 29. Ng1 Qg6 30. Kh1 hxg3 31. hxg3 Qh6 32. Kg2 Rc1 $19) 27. Kg1 Ng4 28.
Ra1 ({The necessity to defend the back rank becomes obvious in the following
variation:} 28. Ndf3 Nxf3+ 29. Nxf3 Qf6 30. Ne1 Rc1 $1 31. Qd2 Qf3 32. Bf1 Qd1
33. Qxd1 Rxd1 34. Nf3 {White is paralysed and there is little wonder that
Black has a convincing winning plan:} b6 35. Ra8+ Kh7 36. Ra3 Bb5 37. Nd2 f5
38. exf5 e4 39. Rc3 Ne5 $19 {[%cal Ge5f3] followed by ... Nf3.}) 28... g6 {
Black's domination is so strong that he can afford alternating attacking moves
with neutral ones.} (28... Qb6 {was premature due to} 29. Nc4) ({The best way
to prepare the queen's incursion on the dark squares was} 28... Bb5 $1 29. Bxb5
(29. Nb3 {runs into} Rc2 $1 30. Bxc2 Ne2+ {mating next.}) 29... Qb6 $1 {
Threatening ... Ne2.} 30. Nc4 (30. Nb3 Rc2 $1 $19 {renews the threat with gain
of time.}) 30... Qxb5 31. Ne3 Ne2+ {mating with the same mechanism.}) 29. Nb3
Nxb3 30. Qxb3 Qb6 31. Qb2 Rc3 32. Ra2 Qd4 33. Qd2 Nf6 {White does not have a
favourable way to defend e4.} 34. Qh6 {Desperation.} (34. Rc2 Rb3 35. Rc4 {
fails to neutralise the pressure due to} Rb2 $1) ({And if} 34. Qe2 Rc1 $19)
34... Rxd3 35. Ra8+ Ne8 {0-1 (35) Dumitrache,D (2431)-Gupta,A (2603) Iasi 2015}
0-1

