1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 Nc6 3. Nf3 e6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Qe7 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8.
O-O a5 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Nb8 11. Ne1 O-O 12. b3 ({The most active line goes} 12.
Nd3 Na6 13. a3) (12. a3 {is premature due to} a4) 12... Na6 13. a3 Bd7 14. Nd3
c6 15. dxc6 Bxc6 $5 {With the pawn on b4, as in our repertoire lines, this
would not be possible.} ({The structure resulting after} 15... bxc6 $11 {
is easier to understand. Black gets the d4-square for his knight without
conceding control over d5. This situation is explained in detail in the
theoretical section. The structure after the text move is once again better
for Black than in the King's Indian, as he does not have a "bad" bishop.}) 16.
b4 axb4 17. axb4 b5 {This is Black's typical counterplay in this structure. We
can now understand one of the reasons why it is a good idea to induce Nbxd2
with an early ...Nc6.} ({Black could have also prepared the pawn break with} 
17... Nc7 {in order to answer cxb5 with ... Nxb5, as if} 18. b5 Bd7 19. Nb4 Ne6
20. Nb3 Rfc8 {Black has excellent control of the dark squares.}) 18. Qc2 bxc4
19. Qxc4 (19. Nxc4 {looks more active, but the knights are hanging a bit after}
Bb5 20. Ra5 Nc7) 19... Qb7 $15 {As a result of the pawn break Black has the
more compact pawn structure. The b-pawn can be easily blocked and is likely to
become a target rather than a passer. Moreover, White's knights are far away
from d5, preventing White from maintaining control.} 20. Ra5 Rfb8 21. Rb1 Bb5
22. Qb3 Nc7 23. Nb2 ({White misses the active} 23. Nf4 {that would have solved
part of his problems:} Qb6 ({But not} 23... exf4 24. e5 $1) 24. Nd5 Ncxd5 25.
exd5 Ra7 {Black's structure remains more compact, but at least there will be
no black knight on d4.}) 23... Ne6 $1 24. Nbc4 Nd4 25. Qb2 Qc7 26. Rxa8 Rxa8
27. Ne3 {Black has achieved a dream position but now starts playing less
accurately.} Bd3 ({The bishop was well placed on b5 and Black did not need to
waste a tempo to provoke the rook exchange, as this was what White would do
anyway. Here is a more coherent plan:} 27... h5 28. h4 Qb6 29. Ra1 Rxa1+ 30.
Qxa1 g6 {Restricting the e3-knight.} 31. Qa5 Qc6 32. Qa3 Ng4 $5 {Weakening
White's defence on both wings. The c2-square and the g1-a7 diagonal become
vulnerable now.} ({Black's position is so strong that even the neutral} 32...
Kg7 $17 {optimising the kingside configuration, would retain a clear advantage.
}) 33. Nxg4 hxg4 $17 34. Qb2 $2 {It is illustrative that this natural move,
preventing ...Qc2, loses by force.} Ne2+ 35. Kh2 Qb6 $19 {[%csl Rf2,Rg3,Rh4]
[%cal Gf2g3,Gb6f2,Gg3h4] White cannot parry ...Qxf2 with mate in sight.}) 28.
Ra1 Rxa1+ 29. Qxa1 Qb7 ({Black should have found a moment to control f5 with} 
29... g6) 30. h3 h5 31. Qa3 Qb5 32. Kh2 (32. Nf5 Nxf5 33. exf5 {would have
freed White a bit.}) 32... g6 $1 {Black still has some advantage, but the
queen and bishop battery fails to impress. Fortunately for him, White decides
to commit positional suicide.} 33. g4 $4 hxg4 34. hxg4 Kg7 35. Qc3 Ne6 36. f3
Nf4 37. Ndc4 Qb8 38. Bf1 Bxf1 39. Nxf1 {0-1 (39) Harikrishna,P (2563)-Gupta,A 
(2335) Nakhchivan 2003} 0-1

