{[#] Since ...b7-b5 is such an effective plan in the structure after dxc6 Bxc6,
I will now reiterate a question from an earlier example. What if White
prevents it with a4? The next example gives us some answers. The position is
almost identical to that from the previous game, but Black has provoked f2-f3
with ... Bg4.} 1. a4 {This stabilizes the queenside but offers Black absolute
control over b4 and c5.} Nd7 2. Nb1 {Intending to transfer the knight closer
to b5 and d5.} f5 $6 {This is a bit premature.} ({Black should have first
strengthened his position to the maximum and only then broken with ...f7-f5.
For instance:} 2... Ndc5 3. Nc3 Qg5 4. Kh1 Nxd3 5. Qxd3 Nc5 6. Qd1 (6. Qxd6
Nxb3 {ruins White's structure.}) (6. Qc2 {exposes the queen to the exchange,
turning b3 into an even bigger weakness.} f5 7. exf5 Qxf5 $1 {This would not
have been available in the game after White's best reaction.} 8. Qxf5 Rxf5 9.
Rab1 g5 {Preventing the freeing attempt f3-f4.} 10. Nb5 Rd8 $17) 6... Rad8 7.
Ra2 {Planning the same regrouping as recommended before.} Qe3 $1 8. Qc2 h5 9.
h4 g6 {, followed by ... f7-f5.}) 3. Nf2 $2 {White should not have accepted
the creation of another weakness on e4.} (3. exf5 $1 {was necessary, with the
following possible regrouping:} Rxf5 4. Ra2 Nac5 5. Nc3 {and White's position
remains harmonious.}) 3... fxe4 4. fxe4 (4. Nxe4 {only makes things worse
because it allows Black to play with a good knight against a bad bishop.} Bxe4
5. fxe4 Rxf1+ 6. Bxf1 Nb4 7. Nc3 Nc5 $17) 4... Ndc5 {Black's knights start
dancing on the available squares.} 5. Nc3 Ne6 6. Rb1 Nac5 7. Ne2 Be8 $5 {
An interesting manoeuvre with the purpose of weakening White's position even
more.} 8. Qd2 ({White has to keep d4 defended, as if} 8. Nc3 Nd4 9. Nd5 Qg5 $19
{Black's domination is crushing.}) 8... Bh5 $1 {Threatening ...Bxe2 followed
by ...Nd4.} 9. g4 {Not really a solution to White's problems, as f4 becomes a
new chronic weakness.} Bg6 ({More elegant and effective would have been to
send the bishop all the way back after having done its kingside job:} 9... Be8
10. Ng3 g6 {followed by ...Bc6.}) 10. Rfd1 $2 {This justifies Black's last
move.} (10. Ng3 $15 {planning ...Nf5, still offered hope.}) 10... Rxf2 $1 11.
Kxf2 Bxe4 ({Even stronger would have been} 11... Nxe4+ 12. Bxe4 Bxe4 $19 {
threatening many things, ...Qh4+ being one of them, while also attacking the
rook. One possible finish is} 13. Ng3 Rf8+ 14. Kg1 Ng5 $19) 12. Kg1 (12. Rbc1 {
offers Black two pawns for the exchange and a devastating attack:} Qh4+ 13. Kg1
Qxg4 14. Ng3 Bxg2 15. Qxg2 Nf4 $19) 12... Bxb1 13. Rxb1 Qg5 14. Qxg5 Nxg5 15.
Nc3 Nge6 $17 {Black has won a pawn, but the bishop is alive now. Loginov went
on to win a long game.} *

